## Who can use them

- Anyone with read access can view active rulesets; admins or roles with **edit repository rules** can create, edit, or delete them.
- Availability: public repos on Free; public and private repos on Pro/Team/Enterprise. Push rulesets need GitHub Team for private/internal repos (and their forks).
- You can allow bypass for specific people, teams, or GitHub Apps when exceptions are required.
- Repositories and organizations can have up to **75 rulesets** each.

## Targeting branches or tags

- Rulesets are named collections applied to branches/tags via `fnmatch` patterns.
- Multiple rulesets can target the same ref; rules are aggregated and the most restrictive version of any overlapping rule wins.
- Example patterns: `releases/**/*` (all release branches), `v*` (tags starting with v), `docs/**` (docs-only branches).

